00:42:08.520 --> 00:42:10.030
- So I'm using the,

00:42:10.030 --> 00:42:12.970
instead of talking about whether it was

00:42:12.970 --> 00:42:15.270
another new deal or not
in just descriptive terms

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:18.940
we, and this grew out of the
project that a bunch of us

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:20.890
did together as well as my own work,

00:42:20.890 --> 00:42:24.410
looked at what it was like in the 30s

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:27.940
for a reform oriented Democrat to appear

00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:31.520
with big majorities in the
middle of a economic crisis

00:42:31.520 --> 00:42:34.000
and compare that to another time 2008

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:34.980
when the same thing happened

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:36.700
and the purpose of the comparison

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:41.210
was to clarify differences
as well as to see

00:42:41.210 --> 00:42:42.650
what might be similar.

00:42:42.650 --> 00:42:45.830
So we noticed several things

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:47.460
I mean the first and most important

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:49.530
is the economic crisis itself.

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:52.930
I mean Roosevelt comes to the New Deal

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:55.200
three years into the Great Depression,

00:42:55.200 --> 00:42:57.173
25 percent unemployment,

00:42:58.010 --> 00:42:59.640
people from both political parties

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:01.550
begging him to do something

00:43:01.550 --> 00:43:04.510
and Congress passing the bills

00:43:04.510 --> 00:43:07.150
before they even got
the written legislation

00:43:07.150 --> 00:43:11.010
in the early period and
that's because the crisis

00:43:11.010 --> 00:43:15.090
was so deep, so obvious,
that the need for action

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:16.920
was for at least a little while accepted

00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:18.743
by everybody across the spectrum.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:23.090
Look at Obama, he
basically is holding hands

00:43:23.090 --> 00:43:24.000
with Herbert Hoover.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:27.170
I mean he comes into office
just at the very beginning

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:29.240
of a financial meltdown
that's going to lead

00:43:29.240 --> 00:43:32.650
to deep economic collapse
and unemployment,

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:35.100
high unemployment, but it hadn't yet,

00:43:35.100 --> 00:43:37.730
so he gets involved in
trying to prevent it

00:43:37.730 --> 00:43:40.200
from turning into a
second Great Depression

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:42.800
and that means he isn't
reaping the sort of

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:45.620
bipartisan support or
the popular understanding

00:43:45.620 --> 00:43:48.570
of the need for many of the things he did.

00:43:48.570 --> 00:43:51.730
So that's one, and another
very different part

00:43:51.730 --> 00:43:54.920
is in context, hyper-partisan
by the time he arrives,

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:58.320
media that include a
right-wing media empire

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:00.340
that can get out a message instantly

00:44:00.340 --> 00:44:02.050
while the rest of the media is fragmented

00:44:02.050 --> 00:44:04.300
and he can't get his message across.

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:07.000
But you're pointing to the final thing,

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:11.750
which is it's a big difference
between putting in place

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:15.950
major reforms in government
for the first time,

00:44:15.950 --> 00:44:17.180
people can understand what you're doing,

00:44:17.180 --> 00:44:19.750
they may not support it,
but they understand it,

00:44:19.750 --> 00:44:23.220
versus trying to change the direction

00:44:23.220 --> 00:44:25.990
of an already massive federal government

00:44:25.990 --> 00:44:29.120
that has its finger in
every sector of the economy

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.240
and that is providing benefits to some

00:44:31.240 --> 00:44:33.200
and doing less for others.

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:37.160
And so we do a lot with that comparison,

00:44:37.160 --> 00:44:39.280
I do a lot with that comparison.

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:41.960
- And if you take health
care, which you discussed,

00:44:41.960 --> 00:44:46.960
that's really an example of a problem set

00:44:46.960 --> 00:44:49.070
where you have vested interests

00:44:49.070 --> 00:44:54.070
who can be very loud in in
opposing inner obstacles

00:44:55.150 --> 00:45:00.150
and on the one hand who
you've got to deal with,

00:45:00.290 --> 00:45:04.690
make deals with, pay
off in order to achieve

00:45:04.690 --> 00:45:06.300
that your progressive goals.

00:45:06.300 --> 00:45:10.190
And all of this is done
behind closed doors

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:13.310
undercover in a way,

00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:16.300
because that's what the system has become.

00:45:16.300 --> 00:45:18.710
- Yeah, and you know health
care is a very good example,

00:45:18.710 --> 00:45:20.270
college student loans too.

00:45:20.270 --> 00:45:23.090
In both cases you already
have the federal government

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:28.090
involved usually by providing
subsidies to private actors

00:45:28.210 --> 00:45:29.690
to give things to people.

00:45:29.690 --> 00:45:32.630
In the case of college
loans, banks were subsidized

00:45:32.630 --> 00:45:34.830
to provide loans to college students.

00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:37.710
In the case of health
care, apart from Medicare

00:45:37.710 --> 00:45:40.290
and Medicaid, which are
government-run programs,

00:45:40.290 --> 00:45:41.680
a lot of the way the federal government

00:45:41.680 --> 00:45:43.530
has been involved in
health care in the past

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:47.820
has been to subsidize
employers with tax breaks

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:50.170
to get them to provide insurance coverage.

00:45:50.170 --> 00:45:52.200
Well that had broken down,

00:45:52.200 --> 00:45:57.070
so Obama did campaign saying
I'm gonna change these things,

00:45:57.070 --> 00:45:58.870
I'm gonna give less to the privileged

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:00.380
and squeeze out the resources

00:46:00.380 --> 00:46:03.170
in a fiscally constrained environment

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:07.210
to give more to ordinary
Americans more loans,

00:46:07.210 --> 00:46:08.730
more grants to college students,

00:46:08.730 --> 00:46:12.230
more healthcare to the
people who are uninsured,

00:46:12.230 --> 00:46:13.303
millions of them,

00:46:14.900 --> 00:46:17.810
40 million or so by the
time he came to office.

00:46:17.810 --> 00:46:20.950
But to do that, he had to design

00:46:20.950 --> 00:46:22.820
a very complex piece of legislation

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:26.860
that could get through Congress
that stepped on the toes

00:46:26.860 --> 00:46:29.150
of many vested interests in both cases

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:31.130
who had the capacity to squawk,

00:46:31.130 --> 00:46:32.790
they knew what was happening.

00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:36.280
Hospitals knew if they were
gonna get less in payments,

00:46:36.280 --> 00:46:37.580
pharmaceutical companies knew if they were

00:46:37.580 --> 00:46:40.780
gonna be getting less for
their prescription drugs,

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:42.910
insurance companies, particular,

00:46:42.910 --> 00:46:45.680
knew where this would challenge them,

00:46:45.680 --> 00:46:48.280
but most of the people who
would eventually benefit

00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:51.440
for example from health care, millions,

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:55.070
30 million Americans gonna get
secure health care coverage,

00:46:55.070 --> 00:46:57.610
most Americans gonna get a better deal

00:46:57.610 --> 00:46:58.690
from the insurance companies.

00:46:58.690 --> 00:47:01.700
They didn't know what they
were eventually going to get,

00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:05.510
so Obama ended up looking
like he was making

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:09.700
a lot of dirty inside deals,
the Cornhusker kickback

00:47:09.700 --> 00:47:11.880
to get Ben Nelson to vote for the thing

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:16.880
and deals with Mary Landrieu in Louisiana

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:20.120
and it looked partisan and
it looked like an inside deal

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:21.523
and it looked complicated.

00:47:22.550 --> 00:47:24.810
The beneficiaries didn't know what it was

00:47:24.810 --> 00:47:26.770
because so many of the changes were in

00:47:26.770 --> 00:47:30.350
these complex regulations and tax breaks

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:33.460
and the opponents knew
exactly what was happening,

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:36.060
so that's part of the reason that you get

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:39.900
the first two years
resulting in a huge blow back

00:47:39.900 --> 00:47:44.330
from opponents and disappointment
from many supporters

00:47:44.330 --> 00:47:47.480
who don't realize the enormity

00:47:47.480 --> 00:47:50.350
of the Obama administration's
accomplishments.

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:52.370
- And this gets at what we
were talking about earlier,

00:47:52.370 --> 00:47:54.860
the contradiction in the American system

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:57.750
where the ideology of
the country as a whole

00:47:57.750 --> 00:48:01.730
is in one place, but
the reality is another

00:48:01.730 --> 00:48:06.671
and it's bringing that truth
to the American people.

00:48:06.671 --> 00:48:09.710
So they realize how they're benefiting

00:48:09.710 --> 00:48:11.440
and then become supporters,

00:48:11.440 --> 00:48:14.480
but then you go on to
say interestingly enough

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:17.590
that in many ways or at least in some ways

00:48:17.590 --> 00:48:19.650
Obama failed as a communicator.

00:48:19.650 --> 00:48:22.410
- I did, I mean we do talk about the way

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:25.820
in which the media environment
has made it difficult,

00:48:25.820 --> 00:48:29.190
but particularly for economic policy.

00:48:29.190 --> 00:48:33.040
And remember, the big
thing on Americans minds

00:48:33.040 --> 00:48:36.740
by the time this president
took office in January of 2009

00:48:36.740 --> 00:48:40.090
was the plunging economy
and Republicans knew

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:41.860
that they were going to
be able to run against him

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:44.940
and against Democrats in a down economy

00:48:44.940 --> 00:48:47.230
because the enormity of the crisis.

00:48:47.230 --> 00:48:49.660
Obama and the Democrats
sponsored the stimulus,

00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:51.800
the American Recovery
and Reinvestment Act,

00:48:51.800 --> 00:48:55.100
but they didn't do a very
good job of explaining

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:58.980
what was in it, why it
was expected to work,

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:00.760
and that was an enormous failure.

00:49:00.760 --> 00:49:03.250
And that's a contrast to FDR,

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:06.020
who even in the darkest
moments of the Great Depression

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:08.360
was always explaining,
he was always explaining

00:49:08.360 --> 00:49:12.380
what he was trying to do
and who was opposed to it.

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:15.290
Obama was facing solid opposition

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:18.280
from a Republican
leadership that had decided

00:49:18.280 --> 00:49:19.570
that it wasn't going to cooperate

00:49:19.570 --> 00:49:21.170
in any of these recovery efforts.

00:49:21.170 --> 00:49:24.370
because they wanted to defeat
this president for re-election

00:49:24.370 --> 00:49:26.880
and Obama kept trying
to reach out to them,

00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:30.550
long beyond the time that was realistic,

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:34.250
but most of all he never
explained what was happening here.

00:49:34.250 --> 00:49:36.340
So I think a lot of ordinary Americans

00:49:36.340 --> 00:49:40.120
who we're now learning in
2012 are willing to give him

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:44.550
a lot of slack on this, are willing to say

00:49:44.550 --> 00:49:46.620
well, maybe it did partly work

00:49:46.620 --> 00:49:48.040
and maybe we should stick with him.

00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:49.950
That's what's happening in this election.

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:51.480
That could have happened earlier

00:49:51.480 --> 00:49:54.300
if only he had explained and he didn't.

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:57.050
- Did it surprise you that
he couldn't communicate?

00:49:57.050 --> 00:49:58.730
- Yeah, I was surprised

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:01.500
because he obviously can communicate.

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:03.710
The question is what happened to him?

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:07.400
And I the only analysis I can
come up with is first of all,

00:50:07.400 --> 00:50:09.840
he was overwhelmed with crises.

00:50:09.840 --> 00:50:12.650
I don't think there have
been very many presidents

00:50:12.650 --> 00:50:14.990
who have arrived in Washington DC

00:50:14.990 --> 00:50:19.580
with more on their plate
because there's two wars,

00:50:19.580 --> 00:50:21.200
one of which he was trying to wrap up

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:25.920
without a signing ceremony on
the deck of a aircraft carrier

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:28.170
or anything like that,
Iraq and another of which

00:50:28.170 --> 00:50:31.400
was fraught with peril, Afghanistan--

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:33.110
- He has a very different
relationship to war

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:36.710
than Roosevelt did, the
war helped Roosevelt

00:50:36.710 --> 00:50:37.600
to get out of the depression.

00:50:37.600 --> 00:50:40.510
- Yeah, and he was trying to
wrap things up in these wars

00:50:40.510 --> 00:50:45.340
or at least intensify
Afghanistan in some ways

00:50:45.340 --> 00:50:46.630
and defeat terrorism and another,

00:50:46.630 --> 00:50:50.600
so it was just a series of
crises he had to deal with

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:53.770
and then there's a economic
meltdown and he's a lawyer,

00:50:53.770 --> 00:50:56.160
he's a constitutional lawyer.

00:50:56.160 --> 00:50:58.670
I think he thought he needed people

00:50:58.670 --> 00:51:02.260
who understood Wall
Street in order to both

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:04.840
recover the economy and
to change Wall Street

00:51:04.840 --> 00:51:09.750
and regulate it, and so he
brought in economic advisors

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:12.350
who frankly did do quite a bit.

00:51:12.350 --> 00:51:16.250
I mean we can all criticize
Larry Summers all we want

00:51:16.250 --> 00:51:18.910
and I have a complicated
personal relationship to him,

00:51:18.910 --> 00:51:22.533
but he did, they did take steps.

00:51:23.570 --> 00:51:24.790
- Not enough.

00:51:24.790 --> 00:51:26.860
- But they didn't focus on employment.

00:51:26.860 --> 00:51:30.810
They focused more on stopping
the economic bleeding

00:51:30.810 --> 00:51:35.050
and the financial collapse
and I don't think that Obama

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:36.970
had people telling him first of all,

00:51:36.970 --> 00:51:40.660
that he should describe
the new investments

00:51:40.660 --> 00:51:43.900
that were in the stimulus,
in new energy sources,

00:51:43.900 --> 00:51:46.590
and job-creating infrastructure projects.

00:51:46.590 --> 00:51:50.160
He should have concretely
stressed those things to voters,

00:51:50.160 --> 00:51:53.470
so they could understand and
he should have talked about

00:51:53.470 --> 00:51:56.420
why government spending
can help the private sector

00:51:56.420 --> 00:51:57.690
because you can't assume that,

00:51:57.690 --> 00:52:00.163
that stuff that my father
explained to me on the street

00:52:00.163 --> 00:52:03.150
in Wyandotte, Michigan when I was a child,

00:52:03.150 --> 00:52:06.860
Americans haven't heard any
of that now for 20 years,

00:52:06.860 --> 00:52:10.280
so how would they know
that government spending

00:52:10.280 --> 00:52:13.250
can actually help economic recovery.

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:14.690
And you had the other side saying

00:52:14.690 --> 00:52:16.780
this is exactly the wrong thing to do.

00:52:16.780 --> 00:52:19.270
I actually think they know
it was the right thing to do,

00:52:19.270 --> 00:52:22.040
but they were gonna say it
was the wrong thing to do

00:52:22.040 --> 00:52:24.040
and Obama didn't counter that

00:52:24.040 --> 00:52:25.710
and I think that was a failure.

00:52:25.710 --> 00:52:29.510
He himself has admitted
recently that it was a failure.

00:52:29.510 --> 00:52:33.463
- And he bought into the
immediate problem is the deficit.

00:52:35.170 --> 00:52:38.540
- Well, he into that a year
later and that is mind boggling.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:40.840
I mean that's just the side of Obama

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:43.073
that wants to reach out to the other side.

00:52:44.420 --> 00:52:45.980
- Now, which leads me to a point.

00:52:45.980 --> 00:52:50.340
I guess one would have to
conclude that running the country

00:52:50.340 --> 00:52:52.860
if you can do that these days is different

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:55.010
than running the Harvard Law Review

00:52:55.010 --> 00:52:58.600
and it used to be said of Lyndon Johnson

00:52:58.600 --> 00:53:00.980
that he would say let us reason together,

00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:05.570
but then he would squeeze
you in a delicate place

00:53:06.640 --> 00:53:07.750
to get you to move.

00:53:07.750 --> 00:53:12.750
So stylistically, Obama has not evidenced

00:53:14.500 --> 00:53:16.450
that part of leadership.

00:53:16.450 --> 00:53:18.380
- Well, that's to some degree true.

00:53:18.380 --> 00:53:20.410
I mean I am not of the school of thought

00:53:20.410 --> 00:53:22.410
that we should be psychoanalyzing him,

00:53:22.410 --> 00:53:26.890
but you're right absolutely
that people's backgrounds

00:53:28.920 --> 00:53:30.280
do tell us something.

00:53:30.280 --> 00:53:33.240
I mean it's both that
he came from academia

00:53:33.240 --> 00:53:36.940
and that he's of his generation
and that he understands

00:53:36.940 --> 00:53:40.870
that many Americans yearn
for a cooperative style

00:53:40.870 --> 00:53:43.830
of politics, so these are genuine things

00:53:43.830 --> 00:53:47.820
that a lot of people want
and Obama does try that.

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.670
He tries to bring people together

00:53:49.670 --> 00:53:51.840
and get them to lay out their ideas

00:53:51.840 --> 00:53:54.140
and then take some from every side.

00:53:54.140 --> 00:53:55.410
I don't think there's anything

00:53:55.410 --> 00:53:56.923
that's not admirable about that.

00:53:56.923 --> 00:53:59.110
I think in many ways it is admirable

00:53:59.110 --> 00:54:01.130
and so the health care reform for example,

00:54:01.130 --> 00:54:03.480
contains lots of Republican ideas

00:54:03.480 --> 00:54:06.097
and I know many progressives
and I consider myself

00:54:06.097 --> 00:54:08.810
and my citizen capacity of
progressives would condemn that.

00:54:08.810 --> 00:54:12.160
I think, you know, I'm not
sure we should condemn it.

00:54:12.160 --> 00:54:15.100
I mean it was a formula for a broadly,

00:54:15.100 --> 00:54:17.789
after all it's Romney's health plan,

00:54:17.789 --> 00:54:22.010
so why not build something
that could get broad support?

00:54:22.010 --> 00:54:26.570
But I don't think Obama was
prepared for the cold blooded

00:54:26.570 --> 00:54:30.980
ruthlessness and the extremism
of the opposition he faced,

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:32.980
which by the time the Tea
Party was in the field

00:54:32.980 --> 00:54:35.380
was also something that
Republicans were going to do

00:54:35.380 --> 00:54:39.300
for their own life because
they'd be often primaries

00:54:39.300 --> 00:54:41.760
if they didn't do it and I don't think

00:54:41.760 --> 00:54:43.850
he reacted soon enough.

00:54:43.850 --> 00:54:48.380
He doubled down in that second
year on cooperative efforts

00:54:48.380 --> 00:54:50.160
and almost did in his presidency

00:54:50.160 --> 00:54:53.920
because they almost sent
the country into default.

00:54:53.920 --> 00:54:55.610
- You've taken in these two books,

00:54:55.610 --> 00:55:00.117
the temperature of the
right's grassroots movement

00:55:02.100 --> 00:55:06.280
and you've taken the temperature
of the Obama administration

00:55:06.280 --> 00:55:08.030
and the progressive disappointment.

00:55:09.220 --> 00:55:11.270
I don't want you to predict the future.

00:55:11.270 --> 00:55:13.400
I don't think that's
something you wanna do,

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:15.210
but I'm curious, what do you think

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:18.610
we should watch for in the coming election

00:55:19.840 --> 00:55:23.660
beyond the mistakes and
errors of Mitt Romney

00:55:23.660 --> 00:55:27.110
you know with regard
to the these big issues

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:31.390
pointing to the country's
future after the election?

00:55:31.390 --> 00:55:33.860
- Well, what we should watch
for is a good way to put it,

00:55:33.860 --> 00:55:36.340
that's what historical
institutional analysis,

00:55:36.340 --> 00:55:38.403
which is what I do can tell you.

00:55:39.470 --> 00:55:41.570
Any social scientist who ever tells you

00:55:41.570 --> 00:55:44.540
that he or she can predict
the future is blowing smoke.

